{"type":"message","id":"814e4dc8","parentId":"d3af2389","timestamp":"2026-04-18T10:17:55.473Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The code is all there. The issue might be that:1. The FE was built and running but the old .next folder might still have the old page cached\n2. The user needs to do a hard refresh or clear the Next.js cache\n\nWait - `yarn start` serves the pre-built files from `.next`. If we did `yarn build` and then `yarn start`, the new code should be served. But maybe the FE build was done AFTER the restart and the build might not have been done with the latest commits.\n\nLet me check - when did the FE get built? We built it after the sync with origin/develop. But the senior-frontend agent committed before that. So the build should include the new code.\n \nThe `.next` folder should contain the latest build since we ran `yarn build` after pulling the new commits, but maybe there's a caching issue with the old `.next` folder still being used. Let me verify when the `.next` was actually built versus when the server started, or if the old build is somehow still being served. I'm realizing the senior-frontend agent made its commit first, and then I pulled in the develop branch changes afterward—so the build should have picked up all the new code. But the user isn't seeing the features, which makes me wonder if Next.js is caching the old static pages and not regenerating them even though `yarn start` should be serving fresh files from `.next`.\n\nThe issue might be that `yarn start` doesn't re-compile on each request like dev mode does—it's just serving the pre-built `.next` output, so if the build was done before the new pages were added, the old version is what gets served. Let me check the file size and modification time of the sat-hach page in `.next` to see if it actually reflects the new build.","thinkingSignature":"393ef37b5721f0c9a61e695b975b4e3b92720a59eb17f586972e6e67205d09f8"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_